Both required outputs have been written and the transcript validates against `transcript_schema.json`.

**Summary of findings**

The dominant pattern in this AML cohort is a single, very large treatment-effect heterogeneity:

- **Venetoclax/azacitidine** raises objective response from 15.8% to 78.6% (RD = +0.628, adjusted OR ≈ 21.6) **only** in the conjunction `npm1_mutation=1 AND unfit_for_intensive=1 AND tp53_mutation=0 AND complex_karyotype=0`. Outside this subgroup the drug is inert (RD = -0.003, p=0.42).
- The triple interaction VEN/AZA × NPM1 × unfit has p ≈ 1e-91; TP53 and complex_karyotype each independently abolish the effect within NPM1+/unfit (p=1e-29 and p=3e-34).
- The other five treatments (7+3, midostaurin, gilteritinib, ivosidenib, enasidenib) had no main effect and no clear positive subgroup. Notably the canonical FLT3-targeted × FLT3 and ivosidenib × IDH1 interactions were null. Enasidenib showed a modest sex-specific signal (interaction p=2e-4); 7+3 was harmful in complex-karyotype patients (interaction p=1e-3).
- Independent prognostic markers (multivariable model): ECOG PS, NPM1, unfit, weight loss, blast %, albumin, CRP, WBC, TP53, complex karyotype.

20 iterations, 77 hypotheses, 76 analyses recorded.
